## PRIOR FINDINGS (build on these; do NOT duplicate; you MUST surface >=1 that these missed)
- F-15-2 [activation/P0] The planned graph is cyclic because P2 needs a parity harness, P3 waits for P2, and the benchmark harness waits for P3 eligibility.
- F-15-3 [benchmark/P0] The benchmark contract forces flag value 1 and therefore cannot verify the P4 unset-default or explicit-zero kill-switch semantics.
- F-15-4 [unnamed/P0] Manifest-derived eligibility lacks an explicit archetype boundary even though four non-hub routers use a different activation contract and remain legacy-authoritative.
- F-15-5 [sk-doc-templates/P1] P4 lockstep names hub directives but omits the create-skill templates that deliberately encode exact default-off wording.
- F-15-6 [activation/P0] The enumerated P4 gate can pass without completed feature catalogs, manual playbooks, durable benchmark evidence, or LUNA verification.
- F-15-7 [playbooks/P1] The benchmark alignment explicitly excludes real models, so deterministic parity and the required LUNA HIGH routed-subject proof need separate gates that join before cutover.
- F-16-1 [activation/P0] HUB_CHILD is a runtime engine-dispatch table, not merely the duplicate eligibility allowlist ADR-002 assumes it is.
- F-16-2 [activation/P0] Copying resolve.cjs alone cannot remove spec-tree coupling because its activation root and compiled engine dependency closure are both resolved relative to the current spec directories.
- F-16-3 [activation/P0] The current serving manifest lacks the hub identity, engine locator, and source-hash data required to implement valid-fresh-manifest eligibility without another mapping.
- F-16-4 [sk-code-align/P0] verify_alignment_drift.py has no cross-file contract mechanism capable of checking eligibility equality, resolver-copy freshness, or forbidden runtime-to-spec imports.
- F-16-5 [unnamed/P1] The compiled engine cache is keyed only by hub ID and therefore would retain a stale snapshot if the promoted resolver becomes long-lived across a manifest re-mint.
- F-10-1 [benchmark/P0] The Lane C verdict enum has no degraded/expected slot for drift-to-legacy fallback, so the new compiledRouting parity gate will collapse three observably distinct states (compiled-serving-with-route-gold-violation, drifted-legacy-fallback, broken-resolver) into one BLOCKED signal — directly violating 012 REQ-004 which mandates drift be scored as degraded/expected.
- F-10-2 [benchmark/P1] reduceRouteTelemetry emits telemetryMissingRate/routeMissRate/aliasMissRate/bundleMissRate for the legacy replay only; the planned compiledRouting block is a sibling block, not a parallel compiled.telemetryMissingRate row, so an operator reading report.advisorySignals.routeTelemetry cannot distinguish a hub whose compiled path is silently failing from one whose compiled path is healthy.
- F-10-3 [activation/P0] No CLI ships a per-hub serving-status readout. 012 REQ-004 mandates it (compiled-serving | legacy-fallback | drifted) and 012 tasks.md:86 (T007) is open, but no module path exists; the seven activation manifests are only inspectable by cat'ing seven files, and compiled-route.cjs resolves (hub,prompt) -> decision rather than fleet -> status[].
- F-10-4 [benchmark/P1] isHubTypeSkill (run-skill-benchmark.cjs:68-70) keys route-gold auto-on by hub-router.json file existence, NOT by compiled-eligibility (which requires entry in COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS at advisor-recommend.ts:41-49 AND a manifest at 010-live-activation/activation/<hub>/manifest.json); a hub-type-but-not-compiled-eligible scenario would route-gold ENFORCED while compiledRouting auto -> off, and operators must reason about both flags to know what was scored.
- F-10-5 [unnamed/P0] routeGold.gate.failed (score-skill-benchmark.cjs:1767) is the only blockable verdict that consumes a per-hub mechanism, but the planned OR-combination with compiledRouting.gate.failed in 014 will collapse three observably distinct states into one BLOCKED signal — an operator triaging a P4 rollout cannot tell route drift from manifest churn from engine throw without opening JSON, which defeats the per-hub observability 012 REQ-004 mandates.
- F-10-6 [unnamed/P1] The frozen-scorer pin is duplicated byte-for-byte across three callers — lib/activate-hub.cjs:46-49, lib/flip-serving.cjs:42-45, and the planned compiled-routing-parity.cjs (014 REQ-001) — with no shared source of truth; an intentional pin update can pass activation while parity silently fails (or vice versa), surfacing two different error messages for the same drift.
- F-17-1 [playbooks/P0] The standard per-scenario template omits the typed manifest gold required by topology validation, so newly authored compiled-routing scenarios default to legacy-only gold.
- F-17-2 [sk-doc-templates/P1] The topology validator treats quoted typed workflow and leaf values as literal quotes while the Lane C loader accepts quoted YAML, creating a copyable-template failure mode.
- F-17-3 [benchmark/P1] A report with no typed-gold exclusions bypasses renderer provenance validation and is still emitted as JSON plus renderer-owned Markdown, so archival output alone cannot prove typed compiled parity ran.
- F-12-1 [archiving/P0] No serving-snapshot.json schema exists per hub that joins manifest + fence + flip + live hash + flag + parity into one durable, machine-readable artifact; the current per-hub evidence is split across activation-record.json, fence-state.json, manifest.json, and serving-flip-record.json under the spec tree.
- F-12-2 [activation/P0] No CLI/MCP/plugin module path is named for the fleet-wide per-hub serving probe, so 012 spec.md:133 / plan.md:158 / tasks.md:86 T007 (per-hub compiled-serving | legacy-fallback | drifted readout) has no concrete implementation surface today.
- F-12-3 [archiving/P0] The 014 Lane C compiled-routing-parity.cjs is planned to write JSON+Markdown to caller-provided --outputs-dir but no spec names a durable hub-local archive location, so a LUNA-high routed-subject run would either pollute the parity dir or vanish after the run.
- F-12-4 [archiving/P1] Both activate-hub.cjs and flip-serving.cjs overwrite their singular audit files (activation-record.json, serving-flip-record.json), silently destroying re-mint history; system-deep-loop already exhibits this with manifest.json fence=3 hash 82d7f3... versus serving-flip-record.json fence=3 hash 7b5491... — a re-mint with no audit row.
- F-12-5 [activation/P1] spec_kit_skill_advisor_status (mk-skill-advisor.js:826-861) already runs at session start, has 22 emitted rows, and is the lowest-blast operator-facing augmentation point for per-hub serving state, yet none of its rows read the 7 activation manifests.
- F-12-6 [unnamed/P1] create-skill (013 spec) plans to mint a manifest for --compiled-routing ready hubs but no spec names where the manifest lives; until the spec-tree 010-live-activation path is populated AND COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS (advisor-recommend.ts:41) is updated AND the fleet probe is wired, a freshly-scaffolded compiled-ready hub is invisible to every observability surface.
- F-12-7 [activation/P2] No plugin or tool wires the runtime front door's (hub,prompt) decision with a session-start fleet probe and writes/updates a per-hub serving snapshot; the mk-dist-freshness-guard.js pattern (compiled-output staleness detection for MCP dist artifacts) lifts directly into a parallel mk-compiled-routing-snapshot.js but no spec names it.
- F-14-1 [activation/P0] manifest.serving-prior.json is captured only on the first flip ever (flip-serving.cjs:125 if-exists guard) and is never refreshed by activate-hub.cjs swapping manifest.json, so a P4a re-mint followed by flip+rollback restores the wrong generation
- F-14-2 [activation/P0] activate-hub.cjs has no operator-facing --rollback command (parseArgs accepts only --hub/--child/--verify/--json) even though flip-serving.cjs implements --rollback, making P4a recovery an unscripted manual file edit
- F-14-3 [activation/P0] The production kill-switch is bi-state (literal '1' on, everything else off) at both read sites, so it cannot implement the P4 default-on target that requires distinguishing unset=on from explicit '0'=off
- F-14-4 [unnamed/P1] compiled-route.cjs fails safe to a legacy sentinel on ANY resolver error including a moved or archived spec tree, with no stderr, log, or telemetry — an invisible fleet-wide rollback if 007-unified-refactor-implementation is archived during the 019 program cutover
- F-14-5 [activation/P1] The fence epoch is incremented on both forward flip and rollback (flip-serving.cjs:128 and 105), so the fence value alone cannot tell an operator whether the current state was reached by cutover or by recovery — defeating P4 audit reconstruction
- F-14-6 [unnamed/P1] The launcher's .env/.env.local loader (mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:70-76) runs at module top-level and injects into process.env, but createChildEnv() (line 267) filters through CHILD_ENV_ALLOWLIST (line 99-150) which omits SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING, so the standard 'put it in .env' operator path silently strips the flag from the spawned advisor child
- F-18-1 [playbooks/P0] Lane C live mode does not execute the manual playbook command, evidence, or pass-fail contract because sk-doc scenarios are loaded with null pass criteria and noncritical status.
- F-18-2 [sk-doc-templates/P1] The playbook skill limits scenario verdicts to PASS, FAIL, and blocked SKIP while its root template permits PARTIAL and can declare READY with noncritical partial scenarios.
- F-18-3 [archiving/P0] The current live executor dispatches a reasoning variant but records only the model, so archived output cannot prove the required GPT-5.6 LUNA HIGH configuration.
- F-18-4 [archiving/P1] The benchmark runner overwrites an existing caller-selected report pair even though the durable storage contract declares every run label immutable.
- F-18-5 [activation/P0] Existing real-model acceptance declares completion despite LUNA transport failures, so zero wrong-hub routes is not an all-LUNA-pass criterion.
- F-18-6 [benchmark/P1] Prior LUNA routing evidence contains no gold-bearing holdouts and therefore establishes fitted-prompt behavior rather than routing generalization.
- F-18-7 [unnamed/P1] The raw log records a completed post-flip sweep while the sibling runtime summary still says that sweep was not rerun.
