     3	description: Templates for creating feature-catalog-style inventories with a root catalog, numbered category sections, current frontmatter conventions, and per-feature reference files.
     4	trigger_phrases:
     5	  - "feature catalog template"
     6	  - "root catalog scaffold"
     7	  - "capability inventory template"
     8	  - "numbered category sections"
     9	importance_tier: normal
    10	contextType: general
    11	version: 1.8.0.10
    12	---
    13	
    14	# Feature Catalog Creation - Templates and Standards
    15	
    16	Templates for creating feature catalogs that combine top-level capability inventory with per-feature reference files.
    17	
    18	> **Need the scaffold?** Jump to [§4 Root Catalog Scaffold](#4-root-catalog-scaffold) or [§5 Per-Feature File Scaffold](#5-per-feature-file-scaffold).
    19	
    20	---
    21	
    22	## 1. OVERVIEW
    23	
    24	**Purpose**: Feature catalogs provide a canonical inventory of what a system does today. They organize live capabilities into numbered sections, summarize current behavior in the root document, and point to per-feature reference files for implementation details, tests, and metadata.
    25	
    26	**Key Characteristics**:
    27	- **Inventory-first**: The root catalog acts as the system-level directory and summary surface.
    28	- **Feature-catalog shaped**: The root file uses frontmatter, an H1 intro paragraph, and numbered all-caps H2 section headers.
    29	- **Per-feature files**: Each catalog entry maps to exactly one per-feature file in a category directory.
    30	- **Current-reality focused**: The root and per-feature files describe shipped behavior, not speculative roadmaps unless clearly marked.
    31	- **Reference-rich**: Per-feature files carry source-file tables, implementation anchors, and metadata.
    32	- **Stable naming**: Category directory names and feature file slugs should remain stable after publication.
    33	- **Packet-history free**: Catalogs cite current source files and validation anchors, not spec or phase packet numbers.
    34	
    35	**Location Convention**: `{SKILL_PATH}/feature-catalog/`
    36	
    37	Canonical layout:
    38	
    39	```text
    40	feature-catalog/
    41	├── feature-catalog.md                 # Root inventory and summary catalog
    42	├── category-name/                     # Required per-feature files for category 1
    43	│   ├── feature-name.md
    44	│   └── another-feature-name.md
    45	└── another-category/                  # Required per-feature files for category 2
    46	    └── feature-name.md
    47	```
    48	
    49	**Existing Example**:
    50	- `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/`
    51	
    52	The existing example keeps its legacy underscore root until the repository content migration. New packages emit only the canonical hyphenated layout above.
    53	
    54	---
    55	
    56	## 2. WHEN TO CREATE FEATURE CATALOGS
    57	
    58	| Create a catalog when | Keep simpler when |
    59	|---|---|
    60	| Surface area is too large for a flat README to be trustworthy | System has only a handful of features |
    61	| You need a stable, reviewable list of current capabilities | An existing README or install guide already gives an accurate full inventory |
    62	| Operators, reviewers, or agents need one place to map features to implementation and test anchors | The system is too early or volatile for a maintained catalog to be worth the overhead |
    63	| Manual playbooks, install guides, or specs need a canonical feature reference to link back to | |
    64	
    65	---
    66	
    67	## 3. CATEGORY AND FILE DESIGN
    68	
    69	Each category groups related features under its own directory.
    70	
    71	| Category Purpose | Example Directory | Example File |
    72	|---|---|---|
    73	| Retrieval | `retrieval` | `unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md` |
    74	| Mutation | `mutation` | `memory-indexing-memorysave.md` |
    75	| Tooling and scripts | `tooling-and-scripts` | `admin-cli-bootstrap.md` |
    76	
    77	Directory and file rules:
    78	- Category directories use descriptive kebab-case names such as `category-name` (no numeric prefix).
    79	- Per-feature files use kebab-case names such as `feature-name.md` (no numeric prefix).
    80	- Per-feature snippet order is defined by the root catalog listing order; filenames do not encode order. Display order is owned by the root catalog index (`feature-catalog.md`), not the folder name.
    81	- Published slugs should remain stable unless the feature is intentionally renamed.
    82	
    83	Per-feature file shape:
    84	1. `## 1. OVERVIEW`
    85	2. `## 2. HOW IT WORKS`
    86	3. `## 3. SOURCE FILES`
    87	4. `## 4. SOURCE METADATA`
    88	
    89	---
    90	
    91	## 4. ROOT CATALOG SCAFFOLD
    92	
    93	Copy this scaffold to create `{SKILL_PATH}/feature-catalog/feature-catalog.md`:
    94	
    95	```markdown
    96	---
    97	title: "{SYSTEM_NAME}: Feature Catalog"
    98	description: "Unified reference combining the complete feature inventory and current-reality reference for the {SYSTEM_NAME} system."
    99	trigger_phrases:
   100	  - "{system name}"
   101	  - "{primary capability phrase}"
   102	  - "feature catalog"
   103	last_updated: "{YYYY-MM-DD}"
   104	version: 1.0.0.0
   105	---
   106	
   107	# {SYSTEM_NAME}: Feature Catalog
   108	
   109	This document combines the current feature inventory for the `{SYSTEM_SLUG}` system into a single reference. The root catalog acts as the system-level directory: it summarizes each capability area, describes what the system does today, and points to the per-feature files that carry the deeper implementation and validation anchors.
   110	
   111	---
   112	
   113	## 1. OVERVIEW
   114	
   115	Use this catalog as the canonical inventory for the live `{SYSTEM_SLUG}` feature surface. The numbered sections below group the system by capability area so readers can move from a top-level summary into per-feature reference files without losing implementation or validation context.
   116	
   117	---
   118	
   119	## 2. {CAT1_HEADING}
   120	
   121	### {FEATURE_NAME_1}
   122	
   123	#### Description
   124	
   125	{FEATURE_DESCRIPTION_1}
   126	
   127	#### Current Reality
   128	
   129	{CURRENT_REALITY_SUMMARY_1}
   130	
   131	#### Source Files
   132	
   133	See [`{CAT1_DIR}/{FEATURE_FILE_1}`]({CAT1_DIR}/{FEATURE_FILE_1}) for full implementation and test file listings.
   134	
   135	---
   136	
   137	### {FEATURE_NAME_2}
   138	
   139	#### Description
   140	
   141	{FEATURE_DESCRIPTION_2}
   142	
   143	#### Current Reality
   144	
   145	{CURRENT_REALITY_SUMMARY_2}
   146	
   147	#### Source Files
   148	
   149	See [`{CAT1_DIR}/{FEATURE_FILE_2}`]({CAT1_DIR}/{FEATURE_FILE_2}) for full implementation and test file listings.
   150	
   151	---
   152	
   153	## 3. {CAT2_HEADING}
   154	
   155	### {FEATURE_NAME_3}
   156	
   157	#### Description
   158	
   159	{FEATURE_DESCRIPTION_3}
   160	
   161	#### Current Reality
   162	
   163	{CURRENT_REALITY_SUMMARY_3}
   164	
   165	#### Source Files
   166	
   167	See [`{CAT2_DIR}/{FEATURE_FILE_3}`]({CAT2_DIR}/{FEATURE_FILE_3}) for full implementation and test file listings.
   168	```
   169	
   170	---
   171	
   172	## 5. PER-FEATURE FILE SCAFFOLD
   173	
   174	Copy this scaffold to create `feature-catalog/{CATEGORY_DIR}/{FEATURE_SLUG}.md`. Both placeholder values must be kebab-case:
   175	
   176	```markdown
   177	---
   178	title: "{FEATURE_NAME}"
   179	description: "{OVERVIEW_ONE_LINE}"
   180	trigger_phrases:
   181	  - "{primary trigger phrase}"
   182	  - "{alternate phrasing}"
   183	  - "{tool or command name}"
   184	  - "{user-visible label if different}"
   185	# importance_tier: "important"   # uncomment only for Tier 1 critical features
   186	version: 1.0.0.0
   187	---
   188	
   189	# {FEATURE_NAME} ({tool_name_or_command})
   190	
   191	<!-- sk-doc-template: skill_asset_feature_catalog -->
   192	
   193	## 1. OVERVIEW
   194	
   195	{OVERVIEW_ONE_LINE}
   196	
   197	{OVERVIEW_DETAIL}
   198	
   199	---
   200	
   201	## 2. HOW IT WORKS
   202	
   203	<!-- Short section (≤3 paragraphs): write plain prose and delete the sub-headings below.
   204	     Long section (>3 paragraphs): keep or rename sub-headings and delete this comment. -->
   205	
   206	### {PRIMARY_BEHAVIOR_ASPECT}
   207	
   208	{Description of the core behavior from the caller's perspective.}
   209	
   210	### {SECONDARY_BEHAVIOR_ASPECT}
   211	
   212	{Description of a distinct aspect — quality gates, routing logic, async behavior, etc.}
   213	
   214	<!-- Add further H3 sub-headings as needed. Common ones:
   215	     Configuration | Quality Gates | Edge Cases | Async & Safety | Post-Action Behavior -->
   216	
   217	---
   218	
   219	## 3. SOURCE FILES
   220	
     1	---
     2	title: Validation - Quality Assessment and Gates
     3	description: Quality gates, DQI scoring, and improvement recommendations for markdown documentation.
     4	trigger_phrases:
     5	  - "dqi scoring bands"
     6	  - "document quality gates"
     7	  - "quality assessment framework"
     8	  - "validation quality dimensions"
     9	importance_tier: important
    10	contextType: general
    11	version: 1.8.0.19
    12	---
    13	
    14	# Validation - Quality Assessment and Gates
    15	
    16	Quality gates, DQI scoring, and script-assisted AI analysis for markdown documentation.
    17	
    18	---
    19	
    20	## 1. OVERVIEW
    21	
    22	### What Is Validation?
    23	
    24	Validation provides a comprehensive quality assessment framework for markdown documentation. The `extract_structure.py` script parses documents into structured JSON; AI uses this data to evaluate quality across structure, content, and style dimensions.
    25	
    26	**Core Purpose**:
    27	- **Quality assessment** - AI-evaluated judgement across structure, content, and style
    28	- **Quality gates** - Document-specific thresholds for production readiness
    29	- **Improvement guidance** - Actionable recommendations based on AI analysis
    30	- **Checklist validation** - Automated structural checks via script
    31	
    32	> **📍 Context**: This is a Level 3 reference file (loaded on-demand). For the complete progressive disclosure architecture, see [skill_creation/overview.md § Skill Structure System](../../create-skill/references/shared/overview.md#3-skill-structure-system).
    33	
    34	This reference provides deep-dive technical guidance on qualitative assessment, quality gates, and interpretation patterns.
    35	
    36	### Core Principle
    37	
    38	**"Measure what matters, gate what guarantees quality"** - Structure ensures validity, Content ensures AI-friendliness, Style ensures consistency. AI evaluates all dimensions based on `extract_structure.py` output.
    39	
    40	---
    41	
    42	## 2. SCRIPT-ASSISTED AI EVALUATION
    43	
    44	**Two-stage validation pipeline:**
    45	
    46	### Stage 1: Format Validation (validate_document.py)
    47	
    48	**Pre-delivery format checks with blocking errors:**
    49	
    50	```bash
    51	python scripts/validate_document.py document.md
    52	# Exit 0 = valid, Exit 1 = blocking errors, Exit 2 = file error
    53	```
    54	
    55	**Checks:**
    56	| Check | Severity | Auto-Fixable |
    57	|-------|----------|--------------|
    58	| Missing required section | blocking | No |
    59	| Non-sequential numbering | warning | No |
    60	
    61	**Options:**
    62	- `--json` - Output results as JSON
    63	- `--fix` - Apply auto-fixes for safe issues
    64	- `--fix --dry-run` - Preview fixes without applying
    65	- `--type readme|skill|reference|asset|agent` - Explicit document type
    66	
    67	**MANDATORY**: Run `validate_document.py` before delivery. Exit code 0 required.
    68	
    69	### Stage 2: Quality Assessment (extract_structure.py)
    70	
    71	**Validation uses `extract_structure.py` to parse documents, then AI evaluates:**
    72	
    73	```
    74	INPUT: Markdown Document
    75	    ↓
    76	SCRIPT: extract_structure.py
    77	    - Parses frontmatter (values + issues)
    78	    - Extracts structure (headings, sections, code blocks)
    79	    - Calculates metrics (word count, heading depth, code ratio)
    80	    - Runs type-specific checklist
    81	    - Generates evaluation questions
    82	    ↓
    83	OUTPUT: Structured JSON
    84	    ↓
    85	AI EVALUATION:
    86	    - Reviews checklist results
    87	    - Answers evaluation questions
    88	    - Assesses content quality
    89	    - Provides recommendations
    90	    ↓
    91	RESULT: Quality Assessment + Recommendations
    92	```
    93	
    94	---
    95	
    96	## 3. CHECKLIST-BASED VALIDATION
    97	
    98	### Structure Checklist (from extract_structure.py)
    99	
   100	The script runs type-specific checklists and reports pass/fail results:
   101	
   102	**Common Checks** (all document types):
   103	- ✅ Single H1, no duplicates
   104	- ✅ Proper heading hierarchy (no skipped levels)
   105	- ✅ Code blocks properly fenced
   106	- ✅ No unclosed markdown elements
   107	- ✅ Section separators (`---`) correct
   108	- ✅ H3/H4 semantic emoji correct (only in RULES sections)
   109	
   110	**SKILL-Specific Checks** (14 checks total):
   111	- ✅ `frontmatter_exists` - YAML frontmatter present
   112	- ✅ `name_present` - Has name field
   113	- ✅ `name_hyphen_case` - Name is hyphen-case (lowercase, digits, hyphens only)
   114	- ✅ `description_present` - Has description field
   115	- ✅ `description_single_line` - Description is single line (no YAML multiline)
   116	- ✅ `allowed_tools_present` - Has allowed-tools field
   117	- ✅ `allowed_tools_array` - allowed-tools in array format `[Tool1, Tool2]`
   118	- ✅ `has_when_to_use` - Has WHEN TO USE section
   119	- ✅ `has_how_it_works` - Has HOW IT WORKS or HOW TO USE section
   120	- ✅ `has_rules` - Has RULES section
   121	- ✅ `h2_numbered` - H2s have number prefix format
   122	- ✅ `no_toc` - No table of contents section
   123	- ✅ `no_placeholders` - No placeholder markers ([TODO], [PLACEHOLDER], etc.)
   124	- ✅ `code_has_language` - Code blocks have language tags
   125	
   126	**README-Specific Checks**:
   127	- ✅ No frontmatter (or optional)
   128	- ✅ Clear purpose/introduction section
   129	- ✅ Usage examples present
   130	
   131	**Checklist Results** in JSON:
   132	```json
   133	{
   134	  "checklist": {
   135	    "results": [
   136	      {"check": "single_h1", "status": "pass"},
   137	      {"check": "frontmatter_valid", "status": "pass"},
   138	      {"check": "description_single_line", "status": "fail", 
   139	       "message": "Description uses multiline format"}
   140	    ],
   141	    "passed": 8,
   142	    "failed": 1,
   143	    "total": 9
   144	  }
   145	}
   146	```
   147	
   148	### Content Quality (AI-Evaluated)
   149	
   150	AI evaluates content based on extracted data and evaluation questions:
   151	
   152	**Evaluation Questions** (generated by script):
   153	- Is the purpose clear from the introduction?
   154	- Are examples practical and complete?
   155	- Is information well-organized and scannable?
   156	- Are there any gaps in coverage?
   157	
   158	**AI Assessment Criteria**:
   159	- Clarity and completeness
   160	- Practical usefulness
   161	- AI-friendliness (scannable, question-answering format)
   162	- Appropriate level of detail
   163	
   164	### Style Compliance (AI-Evaluated)
   165	
   166	AI checks style based on core-standards.md:
   167	
   168	**Key Style Checks**:
   169	- ✅ H2 numbered headings: ALL CAPS (e.g., `## 1. WHEN TO USE`)
   170	- ✅ H3/H4 RULES headings: Only semantic emojis (✅ ❌ ⚠️), no decorative emojis
   171	- ✅ Code examples include comments
   172	- ✅ Bullet lists under 7 items
   173	- ✅ Consistent terminology
   174	- ✅ Active voice preferred
   175	
   176	---
   177	
   178	## 4. DOCUMENT QUALITY INDEX (DQI)
   179	
   180	The `extract_structure.py` script computes a **Document Quality Index (DQI)** - a 100% deterministic score from 0-100 based on measurable document attributes. This replaces subjective AI-only assessment with quantifiable metrics.
   181	
   182	### DQI Components
   183	
   184	| Component | Max | What It Measures |
   185	|-----------|-----|------------------|
   186	| **Structure** | 40 | Checklist pass rate (type-specific validation) |
   187	| **Content** | 30 | Word count, heading density, code examples, tables/lists, links |
   188	| **Style** | 30 | H2 formatting (number+CAPS), section dividers, intro paragraph |
   189	
   190	### Content Score Breakdown (30 points)
   191	
   192	| Metric | Max | Criteria |
   193	|--------|-----|----------|
   194	| Word count | 10 | Within type-specific range (e.g., skills: 2000-8000 words) |
   195	| Heading density | 8 | Appropriate H2 count per 500 words |
   196	| Code examples | 6 | 3+ code blocks with language tags = full points |
   197	| Tables/lists | 3 | Presence of tables (+2) and lists (+1) |
   198	| Links | 3 | Internal links (+2) and external links (+1) |
   199	
   200	### Style Score Breakdown (30 points)
   201	
   202	| Metric | Max | Criteria |
   203	|--------|-----|----------|
   204	| H2 formatting | 12 | Number + ALL CAPS on H2 headings |
   205	| Section dividers | 6 | Horizontal rules between H2 sections |
   206	| Style issues | 8 | Penalty of -2 per style issue detected |
   207	| Intro paragraph | 4 | Brief introduction after H1 |
   208	
   209	### Quality Bands
   210	
   211	| Band | Score Range | Status | Action |
   212	|------|-------------|--------|--------|
   213	| **Excellent** | 90-100 | ✅ Production-ready | None needed |
   214	| **Good** | 75-89 | ✅ Shareable | Minor improvements recommended |
   215	| **Acceptable** | 60-74 | ⚠️ Functional | Several areas need attention |
   216	| **Needs Work** | <60 | ❌ Not ready | Significant improvements required |
   217	
   218	### DQI JSON Output
   219	
   220	```json
   221	{
   222	  "dqi": {
   223	    "total": 96,
   224	    "band": "excellent",
   225	    "band_description": "Production-ready documentation",
   226	    "components": {
   227	      "structure": 40,
   228	      "structure_max": 40,
   229	      "content": 26,
   230	      "content_max": 30,
   231	      "style": 30,
   232	      "style_max": 30
   233	    },
   234	    "breakdown": {
   235	      "checklist_pass_rate": 100.0,
   236	      "word_count": 4168,
   237	      "word_count_score": 10,
   238	      "h2_count": 9,
   239	      "heading_score": 8,
   240	      "code_block_count": 8,
   241	      "code_score": 6,
   242	      "h2_format_score": 12,
   243	      "style_issue_count": 0
   244	    }
   245	  }
   246	}
   247	```
   248	
   249	### Key Principles
   250	
   251	1. **100% Deterministic**: Every point is computed from measurable data, not AI judgment
   252	2. **Transparent**: Full breakdown shows exactly where points are earned/lost
   253	3. **Type-Aware**: Thresholds adjust based on document type (skill, reference, asset, etc.)
   254	4. **Actionable**: Low scores in specific components guide improvement priorities
   255	
   256	---
   257	
   258	## 5. QUALITY GATES
   259	
   260	Quality bands are defined in Section 4 (DQI). This section specifies document-specific enforcement requirements.
